Minda Dentler's life is one of inspiration, courage and determination. As an infant in India, she contracted polio, resulting in the paralysis of her legs, and was left at an orphanage. When she was three, she was adopted by an American family which enabled her to receive the medical care necessary to be able to walk with leg braces and crutches.

Undeterred by her disability, Dentler became an independent woman with the intention and drive to face and overcome the many obstacles she has encountered throughout her life. As an adult, she discovered athletics and threw herself into the sport of triathlon. In 2013, she became the first female wheelchair athlete to complete the Ironman World Championship, in Kona, Hawaii.

Dentler is an athlete, speaker, advocate and mother. She has been featured on CNN, Forbes and NBC. She has written for Huffington Post and TIME, advocating for the eradication of polio. She was a 2017 Aspen Institute New Voices Fellow. She works for a large global insurer and, with her husband, is raising a young daughter. She's committed to inspiring people to move beyond their fear of failure and achieve their goals.

title: What I learned when I conquered the world's toughest triathlon

aws-transcripts.transcript: It was October 13th 2012 a day that I will never forget. I was on my bike, pushing up what seemed like a never ending Baron Hill. And it wasn't just any hill. It was a 15 mile climb up to town called Heavy on the Big Island of Hawaii. And it wasn't just any ride. It was at the Iron Man World Championship. I can still feel my muscles burning. I was struggling, tired and dehydrated is I could feel the heat emanating from the asphalt. Measuring almost 98 degrees, I was near the halfway point of the bike portion of one of the most prestigious, longest single day endurance race events in the world. Every year during my childhood, I watched this very race on TV in our family living room. I sat next to my dad on our 19 seventies, that warrant and brown sofa, and I remember being an utter odd how these athletes push themselves to their limit in this grueling race. And just so you don't get the wrong idea. My family members weren't just spectators. They were incredibly athletic, and I always participated from the sidelines cheering on my three siblings are handing out water at local races. I remember wanting so badly to be able to compete, but I couldn't. Even though I couldn't play sports, I decided to be active in my community. I volunteered at the local hospital in high school and college. I intern at the White House, studied abroad in Spain and backpack through Europe all by myself with my leg braces and crutches. Upon graduating, I moved to New York City for a job in management consulting, earned an M B A. Got married. And now I have a daughter. At age 28 I was introduced to the sport of hands likely and then triathlon. And by luck I met Jason Fowler and Iron Man world champion at a camp for athletes with disabilities. And like me, he competed in a wheelchair, and with his encouragement, at age 34 I decided to go after Kona. The Kona or Hawaii Iron Man is the oldest iron distance race in the sport, and if you're not familiar, it's like the Super Bowl of Triathlon in the Iron Man. For wheelchair athlete like Mia consists of ah, 2.4 mile open water. Assuming the Pacific Ocean 112 mile hand cycle ride in lava fields. Now that sounds exotic, but it's not a scenic as it sounds, and it's pretty desolate. And then you top it off with a marathon or 26.2 mile run in 90 degree heat using a racing wheelchair. That's right. It's a total distance of 100 and 40.6 miles, using just your arms in less than 17 hours. No female wheelchair athletes had ever completed the race because of the strict, seemingly impossible cut off times. And so there I waas, putting it all out on the line. And when I finally reached the top of that 15 mile climb, I was discouraged. There was no way I was gonna make that swim like time limit of 10 and 1/2 hours because I was almost two hours off pace. I had to make the agonizing decision to quit. I move my timing chip, but I handed it over to race official. My day was done. My best friend Shannon and my husband, Sean, were waiting at the top of Javi to drive me back to town and on my way back to town I began to cry. I bailed My dream of completing the Iron Man World Championship was crushed. I was embarrassed. I felt like I'd messed up. I'm worried about what My friends, my family and people had worked would think of me. What was I gonna put on Facebook Isn't gonna explain to everyone that things don't go the way I had assumed or planned a few weeks later. Always talking toe Shannon about the Kona disaster. And and she said this to me, Minda. Big dreams and goals can only be realized when you're ready to fail. I knew I had to put that failure behind me in order to move forward. And it wouldn't be the first time that I had faced insurmountable odds. I was born in Bombay, India, and just before my first birthday I contacted polio, which left me paralyzed from the hips down, unable to care for me. My birth mother left me of an orphanage. Fortunately, I was adopted by an American family and I moved us full can Washington Just shortly after my third birthday over the next few years, I underwent the Syrians. The surgeries on my hips, my legs and my back that allowed me to walk with leg braces and crutches. As a child, I struggled with my disability. I felt like I didn't sit in. People stared at me all the time. I was embarrassed about wearing a back brace and leg braces, and I always hid my chicken legs under my pants. As a young girl, I saw thick, heavy braces on my legs. Didn't look pretty or feminine among my generation. I am one of the very few individuals in the U. S. We're living with paralysis by polio today. Many people who contract polio and developing countries do not have access to the same medical care, education or opportunities like I've had in America. Many do not even live to reach adulthood. I have the humbling knowledge that had haven't adopted. I most certainly wouldn't be in front of you today. I may not even be alive.
